{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:21:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2377"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2377"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.02,0.08,0.09,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59103"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44514"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"319"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59103"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of severe right eye pain and blurred vision. She reports seeing coloured halos around lights and has an associated headache and nausea. She has no significant medical history. Her only medication is trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole for a recent urinary tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her right eye shows conjunctival injection and corneal oedema. Visual acuity is 6/6 in the left eye but only finger counting at 1 metre in the right eye. The right pupil is dilated and fixed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical atropine","Topical ciprofloxacin","Topical steroids","Fundoscopy","Intraocular pressure measurement"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of acute angle-closure glaucoma including severe eye pain, blurred vision, coloured halos around lights, fixed dilated pupil, conjunctival injection, and corneal oedema. The condition requires urgent diagnosis and management to prevent permanent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraocular pressure measurement\u003C/strong\u003E is essential to confirm the diagnosis of acute angle-closure glaucoma and guide management. This can be performed using tonometry, which is typically available in emergency departments. Gonioscopy is the gold standard diagnostic tool for angle-closure glaucoma however is only used by ophthalmologists. Once confirmed, urgent treatment to lower intraocular pressure using agents such as topical beta-blockers, alpha-2 agonists, and carbonic anhydrase inhibitors can be initiated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical atropine\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated as it is a mydriatic agent that would worsen the condition by further dilating the pupil and increasing blockage of the trabecular meshwork. While useful in anterior uveitis, it could cause devastating consequences in acute angle-closure glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic used for bacterial eye infections and would not address the underlying pathology of increased intraocular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E are used for inflammatory conditions like anterior uveitis but would not be appropriate for acute angle-closure glaucoma where the priority is reducing intraocular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be difficult to perform due to corneal oedema and is contraindicated as pupillary dilation would worsen the condition. It would not provide useful diagnostic information in this acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute angle-closure glaucoma presents with severe eye pain, blurred vision, fixed dilated pupil, and coloured halos around lights.","Prompt intraocular pressure measurement is essential if acute angle-closure glaucoma is suspected.","Mydriatic agents like atropine are contraindicated in acute angle-closure glaucoma as they worsen the condition."],"references":["Pokhrel PK, Loftus SA. Ocular emergencies. Am Fam Physician 2007; 76:829. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2007/0915/p829.html","Quigley HA. Glaucoma. Lancet 2011; 377:1367. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(17)31469-1/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2377"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44514"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-04T20:58:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-04T20:59:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59103"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false